note.body:
Given that we're using the source cache, `bst source fetch` will try to fetch from there first. What is cached in the source cache are the ready-to-build sources (staged in buildstream's parlance), not the original tarballs or git repositories. So fetching from the source cache doesn't help if we need to pull a different version from upstream.

The speed-up we can gain for track is by having the dedicated volume, where original sources are cached.

The main thing this brings us is that the sources are cached and pushed to the source cache in this job, so that build jobs don't need to do it again (with 3 different jobs racing to do it and ending up doing it in parallel).

target_title: Generate flatpaks of GNOME core apps

note.body:
Though, I wonder if it's easier to just install all apps into the system-wide installation, and each user just maintains a list of apps (and versions) they want installed?

So if user A installs an app, and then user B installs the same app, they're sharing it in the system installation. If user A tries to update the app, they'll download the new version into the system installation but that's it: user B is still using the old version. Once user B updates, we can just clean up the files in the system installation and call it a day.

We'd still need to handle the builtin installations somehow. Either the Android way I propose above, or we can just copy the files from /usr into /var/lib/flatpak on first boot and call it a day

Pros:
- this is much simpler to implement
- we can mount home directories as noexec by default
- we can save disk space this way, by sharing all apps and runtimes between all users

Cons:
- we'd need to leak the user's installed app list to the rest of the system, which might be undesirable. Also means it's not protected by homed
    - counterpoint: most use-cases will either be single-user. And those that aren't often involve parental controls and thus leaking the list of installed apps is a feature, not a bug.
- homed home dirs become less portable. You'd need to install apps on first launch when moving between systems.
    - counterpoint: we can cache app icons and .desktop entries somewhere in the home directory, and then synthesize downlaod-on-launch .desktop entries for the apps that are missing on the current system app repository. So if you move your home dir over to another system, all your apps will stay but when you launch them it'll have to re-download them.
       - This can also be used to implement an iOS-esque "offload" feature, where you delete executables but keep data to save space on disk
       - We can probably grey out the app icons to indicate that the app is "offloaded"? And prompt to re-install it on first launch?

I think this is my current favorite solution.

target_title: Generate flatpaks of GNOME core apps

note.body:
I personally like something in between the Android and iOS solution. Here are my ideas:

- We should have a Flatpak installation in /usr. I'll call this the builtin installation
- GNOME OS will probably get updated as much as the Flatpak runtime and apps. So, in practice 9 times out of 10 users will have no need to copy these files out of /usr and update them independently. Why duplicate the storage space? So we should just run apps directly from /usr
- For circumstances where we really do want to update the Platform/an App independently from the host system (for example: security bug in Epiphany or something), we can copy the files from the builtin installation and to the system installation for updates. Then, once the OS itself is updated, we can delete the app from the system installation again to avoid wasting space.
- We need some infrastructure that sits on top of basic Flatpak installations and mediates between them, similar to Android's PackageManager service.
- We can support uninstalling apps from the builtin (or even system) installations by just hiding those apps for that user. From inside of this PackageManager service.
- The PackageManager service would need to be aware of what Platforms each user account requires, so that it can manage the lifecycle of how "needed" available platforms are.

Basically we have three storage tiers instead of Android's two:
- The user installation. These are apps / platforms that are installed for that specific user. I'd like this to be the default place apps (and "uncommon" runtimes) go when installed from Software
- The system installation. These are apps / platforms that are shared between all users. I'd like this to be the default place the various common Flatpak runtimes go (freedesktop-sdk, KDE, Mesa/Intel/NVIDIA drivers, and old versions of the GNOME Platform). It's also the place where updated versions of apps/platforms fromthe builtin installation go. Finally, administrator users should be able to choose to install apps system-wide (for all users).
- The builtin installation. These are apps/platforms that are shipped out of the box with the OS.

I brainstormed about this last night, here are my notes. Please excuse them if they're unintelligible: https://pad.gnome.org/kOddL3q2TB2UVwWmW-GSAA

target_title: Generate flatpaks of GNOME core apps

note.body:
I did some research about what other OSs do here.

### iOS

iOS has a read-only root partition which is like our /usr, and a writable partition in /private.

Built-in apps are shipped in /Applications, and the "platform" is shipped in /System/Library/Frameworks. Apps installed from the app store are installed into a subdirectory of /private. Some built-in apps are what's called "stagable", and they can be uninstalled. These apps are copied (or, more likely, symlinked) from / into /private at some point (looks like this happens on the first launch for these apps), and can be uninstalled/re-installed by the App store by deleting their copy/symlink in /private. It doesn't apprear that there's any mechanism for Built-in apps or Frameworks to recieve updates independently of the host OS.

iOS is also a bit strange because it kinda lies about the state of things on the rootfs. Nominally, what I say above is true. But in practice, all the the frameworks and built-in executables get glued together into a single file called the "dynamic linker cache" during iOS's mastering process, and the original files are either deleted outright or stubbed out. So when an app is located in /Applications, its executable is simply a stub (with no .text section) that tells the dynamic linker which code to load from the "cache" blob. Apps from the App Store must of course ship real executables, but again they load system-provided libraries from the cache.

### Android

Android has a read-only partition in /system which is like /usr, and a writeable partition in /data which is like /var.

Android has two app installation sites: one in /system (which I'll call "builtin") and another in /data (I'll call this "system"). These two installations are completely owned by the PackageManager service, which acts as the source of truth about what apps are actually available, what versions of those apps to use, and where those bundles are.

Basically, when looking up what apps are installed, the PackageManager scans the builtin installation first, and then scans the system installation. If a package exists in both installations, whichever has a newer version number wins. This way, you can update built-in system apps from the Play Store by just downloading the new version into the system installation. Once the OS itself is updated, the builtin installation may now contain a newer version and it will be used instead.

Android doesn't delete apps from the system installation if a newer version is available in the builtin installation. It assumes that the OS doesn't get frequent updates (which is true for them because OEMs control when an update for their device is released). Thus, it assumes that the copy of the app in /data will be used a lot more than the copy in /system

Android has a very similar system for APEX bundles, which are essentially their equivalent to sysexts and (in some ways) Flatpak runtimes. APEX bundles is seemingly how "Google Play System Updates" are implemented (where Google ships parts of Android directly, bypassing OEMs)

You can "uninstall" system apps by just deleting the updated bundle in /data. The system app remains available, just downgraded to its original version. You can hide the system app by "disabling" it, which just adds the app to a list of hidden apps (and pretends that the app is no longer available).

Android has the concept of multiple users. Users don't have their own app installations. Instead, they all share the system installation, and the PackageManager service keeps track of what packages are installed into what user account. So, let's say I create a Guest user on an Android device. This user starts with no Play Store apps installed, but in practice these apps actually _are_ installed. Lets say the Guest user goes onto the Play Store and installs Instagram. If the main user already had Instagram installed, all that happens is the app appear in the Guest user's account. If the Guest user updates the Instagram app, it's updated for all users on the system. If the Guest user uninstalls the Instagram app, it's just hidden from the user's account but remains on disk because other users still request that the app is installed.

note.body:
> * Archive of flatpak repo in /usr
>   * fine space wise since gnome os happens to be the same content
>   * wouldn't actually be used for anything but local cache
>   * what apple does is show icons for apps but they're not actually installed
>     * when you launch an app it installs from the local cache
>     * endless tried to do this too?
>       * installed in the system ostree repo, not very reliable

Greetings from Endless! We have done the following things in this space. I'm not sure which of these is being referred to here.

## Merged the ostree and systemwide flatpak repos.

`/var/lib/flatpak/repo` was a symlink to `/ostree/repo`.

This made sense when the Flatpaks we preinstalled used a runtime that was built from our OS packages so we got some good deduplication of common files; but we ran into various issues sharing the same repo between ostree and flatpak, and the space-saving went away when Flathub, and the freedesktop & GNOME runtimes came about, so we stopped doing this.

## Preinstalled apps

We preinstall apps in `/var/lib/flatpak` in our install media. This works well enough for us, though it's not possible to do a full factory reset since `/var` lives outside `/usr` and so is not managed as part of the ostree. (Different install images use the same ostree commit but with different stuff in `/etc` and `/var/lib/flatpak`.)

## “Get Foo” launchers

We used to have a thing where we would manually create fake launchers, like “Get Zoom”, which when clicked would launch GNOME Software at the page for Zoom. When you install real Zoom, some magic would occur to replace the fake launcher. This was for extra-data apps that we couldn't actually preinstall for license reasons. It was just a desktop file and icon.

As a special case, Chrome was set as the default browser but not actually installed; on first login we would trigger GNOME Software to install it in the background. In this way we could set Chrome as the default browser without preinstalling it and most users would be none the wiser. If they click the launcher too early then they would be bounced to the GNOME Software page.

We don't do these any more but if I were to do this again, I would do something a little different: build & install a stub Flatpak, ostensibly from the `flathub` remote, which when launched uses the [UpdateMonitor](https://docs.flatpak.org/en/latest/portal-api-reference.html#gdbus-org.freedesktop.portal.Flatpak.UpdateMonitor) to “update” itself to the real remote app. And of course GNOME Software would, in the background, automatically update these fake apps to the real thing.

In my personal opinion, it simply looks worse. Not to mention the abundance of projects already using it.

This is subjective, but I feel like twemoji is really the worst option to go with here, not just because of how it looks, but because I don't think it fits the rest of our design system that well.

Microsoft's emoji (also open source) would probably fit better even if we want to move away from Noto, but why are we even considering this?

Also, designing a custom emoji font seems like it could be fun, at least for some of the more common ones even if we use a fallback for the more obscure graphics.
